05489nam a22008415i 9780812202700DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979622666  a97808122027007 a10.9783/97808122027002doi  a(DE-B1597)449126  a(OCoLC)794702202  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBF1573b.M34 2004eb 7aREL0200002bisacsh04a299/.94/09732221 aMagliocco, Sabina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWitching Culture :bFolklore and Neo-Paganism in America /cSabina Magliocco. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2010] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Ethnography00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Ethnography of Magic and the Magic of Ethnography -- tPart I. Roots and Branches -- t1. The Study of Folklore and the Reclamation of Paganism -- t2. Boundaries and Borders: Imagining Community -- tPart II. Religions of Experience -- t3. Making Magic: Training the Imagination -- t4. Ritual: Between the Worlds -- t5. "The Juice of Ritual": Pathways to Ecstasy -- tPart III. Beyond Experience: Religion and Identity -- t6. The Romance of Subdominance: Creating Oppositional Culture -- t7. "The Heart Is the Only Nation": Neo- Paganism, Ethnic Identity, and the Construction of Authenticity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTaking the reader into the heart of one of the fastest-growing religious movements in North America, Sabina Magliocco reveals how the disciplines of anthropology and folklore were fundamental to the early development of Neo-Paganism and the revival of witchcraft. Magliocco examines the roots that this religious movement has in a Western spiritual tradition of mysticism disavowed by the Enlightenment. She explores, too, how modern Pagans and Witches are imaginatively reclaiming discarded practices and beliefs to create religions more in keeping with their personal experience of the world as sacred and filled with meaning. Neo-Pagan religions focus on experience, rather than belief, and many contemporary practitioners have had mystical experiences. They seek a context that normalizes them and creates in them new spiritual dimensions that involve change in ordinary consciousness.Magliocco analyzes magical practices and rituals of Neo-Paganism as art forms that reanimate the cosmos and stimulate the imagination of its practitioners. She discusses rituals that are put together using materials from a variety of cultural and historical sources, and examines the cultural politics surrounding the movement—how the Neo-Pagan movement creates identity by contrasting itself against the dominant culture and how it can be understood in the context of early twenty-first-century identity politics.Witching Culture is the first ethnography of this religious movement to focus specifically on the role of anthropology and folklore in its formation, on experiences that are central to its practice, and on what it reveals about identity and belief in twenty-first-century North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFolklorezUnited States. 0aNeopaganismzUnited States. 0aRELIGIONvCults. 4aFolklore. 7aRELIGION / Cults.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Religionz978311041358808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Penn